[SN]TITLE[SN]
North Wales Police cleared in child abuse probe delays

[SN]FIRST-SENTENCE[SN]
An inquiry into delays by North Wales Police in investigating information on child abuse provided by an international operation has found no case to answer for any of its staff.

[SN]RESTBODY[SN]
The force was given information from Canadian police in 2013-14 about people who had bought DVDs of naked children.
No action had been taken against three of the people named to them.
The Independent Police Complaints Commission said there had been a system failure rather than individual fault.
Toronto Police passed the names of about 2,000 people to the UK's Child Exploitation and Online Protection Centre (CEOP) from its Operation Spade investigation.
CEOP sent relevant information on to North Wales Police, but when the force started to advise CEOP of the results of their inquiries, they discovered there were three people named who had not been looked at.
North Wales Police referred itself to the IPCC in October 2014, which began its investigation.
It found:
IPCC commissioner Jan Williams said the force had made significant changes to structures which made a recurrence of the situation "extremely unlikely".
North Wales Police's Deputy Chief Constable Gareth Pritchard said: "It was down to the skills and due diligence of the team involved that the problem was both highlighted and dealt with so expediently.
"Their actions undoubtedly protected the victims involved, the reputation of this force and led to learning by all agencies."
One of the most high-profile cases to emerge from Operation Spade was Cardiff deputy head teacher Gareth Williams, who was jailed for five years, later cut to four, for making recordings of pupils in school toilets and possessing indecent images.
